<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
When you use an image from the internet where no author is provided, include the title of the image in double quotation marks immediately after the cited material. Abbreviate the title if it is longer than a noun phrase. For example, <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Southern Novels</em> consists entirely of a noun phrase (a noun <em>Novels</em> preceded by two modifiers) and wouldn&#8217;t be shortened. By contrast <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels of the South</em> would be shortened to its noun phrase <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels</em>. The abbreviated title should begin with the word by which it is alphabetised in the Works Cited. If the title does not begin with a noun phrase, cite the first word if it is enough to direct the reader to the correct entry. For further information on abbreviating titles, see 3.2.1 in the <a href="http://west-sydney-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/UWS-ALMA:default_scope:UWS-ALMA21186157620001571" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MLA Handbook (8th edition)</a>.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;conveys a sense of heightened emotion ("An"). 
</blockquote>
<br><br>
Or include the full name of the image in your sentence.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&#34;An offering to the Ocean in La Punta, Peru&#34;, pictured below, shows&hellip;
</blockquote>
